
[1]ribin

   RIB'IN, n.

   1. A filet of silk; a narrow web of silk used for an ornament, as a
   badge, or for fastening some part of female dress.

   2. In naval architecture, a long narrow flexible piece of timber,
   nailed upon the outside of the ribs from the stem to the sternpost, so
   as to encompass the ship lengthwise; the principal are the floor-ribin
   and the breadth-ribin.

                     RIB'IN, v.t. To adorn with ribins.
